    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "4fbe8de9a634f0b62ae4122baece7efbad0eef802d0325390448a80ff929b137",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "More generally, if $k_1>2$ then for fixed $a$ and $b$\\[a\\prod_{1\\leq i\\leq k_1}(m_1+i)=b\\prod_{1\\leq j\\leq k_2}(m_2+j)\\]should have only a finite number of solutions. \n\nSee also [363], [686], and [931]."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "a4f6a7f7bd3c8d8af9d978fbf7a38b4f82e24cf604fa238d4772fcdf09525235",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Can one classify all solutions of\\[\\prod_{1\\leq i\\leq k_1}(m_1+i)=\\prod_{1\\leq j\\leq k_2}(m_2+j)\\]where $k_1,k_2>3$ and $m_1+k_1\\leq m_2$? Are there only finitely many solutions?"
    }
  },
